That's right! The recurrent branch of the median nerve innervates the opponens pollicis (A) and the flexor pollicis brevis (B). Both of these muscles are thenar muscles.

Recall that the median nerve innervates all muscles in the anterior compartment of the forearm, with one-and-a-half exceptions     . Before passing through the carpal tunnel into the hand, the median nerve gives a palmar branch that passes superficial to the flexor retinaculum to the central region of the palm. This cutaneous branch is not present in your prosection, but is important.

of the median nerve innervating the thenar muscles. Follow the main branch distally, and you might see it innervating the lateral two lumbricals. 
The thenars and the lateral two lumbricals are the only intrinsic muscles of the hand innervated by the median nerve. All others are innervated by the ulnar nerve. 
Any other branches of the median nerve you see are cutaneous (digital) branches. They innervate the skin over the lateral three-and-a-half digits (green region in illustration).
